      <description>Until the mid-18th century, sailors traveling out of sight of land had few ways of measuring their longitude. It could be done if the ship could know the time difference between local time and some set standard. The chronomer allowed for the accurate measure of such a standard time, e.g. GMT. This chronometer is part of the Garland Collection of Scientific Instruments.</description>
